    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Stocks aren&rsquo;t always trending. When they&rsquo;re not trending, they tend to stay sideways (consolidate). During this consolidation period, the range is very narrow, but analogous to a chemical reaction that&rsquo;s just brewing, the stock, upon breaking out, will most likely explode once again and resume trending.</p>

<p>One of those stocks that is set up for such a move is $FNF. Please observe the chart below:</p>

<h3 id="20170206-fnf">$FNF</h3>


<p><a href="/images/blog/20170206/fnf.png"><img src="/images/blog/20170206/fnf.png" alt="$FNF - 2017-02-06 - Daily" /></a></p>

<p>$FNF has been consolidating for the past two trading sessions. Though overbought, conditions may continue to stay overbought for a while. A break above $36.67, with market internals confirming, and we should see this stock run towards $38.50. A potential trade idea is the following:</p>

<p><a href="/images/blog/20170206/fnfoc.png"><img src="/images/blog/20170206/fnfoc.png" alt="FNF Options Chain - 2017-02-06 - Daily" /></a></p>

<p>Consider buying the 36 or 37 call option expiring in 11 days. Buying the 36 call option with $FNF expiring at 38.5 will generate roughly 2.3 * R, while the 37 call option will generate roughly 4 * R. Size your risk appropriately, and to avoid theta decay, consider buying options that are more ITM.</p>

